We solve this problem using Dynamic Programming (DP) by considering partitions of size at most k.

At each index, we try forming a partition of length from 1 to k. For every partition:

Find the maximum element in that subarray
Replace all elements in the partition with this maximum
Add the contribution:
max_element × partition_length

Let dp[i] represent the maximum sum achievable starting from index i.


For each index i, we try all partition sizes:

dp[i] = max(max(arr[i...i+len-1]) * len + dp[i+len])

Where:

len ranges from 1 to k
i + len <= n
dp[n] = 0

When we reach the end of the array, no further contribution is possible.

⏱️ Complexity
Time Complexity: O(n × k)
Space Complexity: O(n)

Instead of trying all possible splits (which is inefficient), we:

Limit partition size to k
Use DP to reuse computed results
Build the solution by making the best local choice at each index
